  "properties": {
    "encrypted": "false",
    "long_instructions": "A student writing a research paper wants to check how their spelling of a word compares to a known dictionary word. This comparison will help them determine if they might have typed it incorrectly.\r\n\r\n✅ **TO DO #1:** In the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">Essay</code> class, complete the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">compareWords()</code> method. This method should:\r\n\r\n- Use <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">compareTo()</code> to compare a typed word (<code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">wordToCheck</code>) with a known dictionary word\r\n- Return the result of the comparison as an integer\r\n\r\n✅ **TO DO #2:** In the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">EssayRunner</code> class, create an <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">Essay</code> object using a dictionary word, then call <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">compareWords()</code> and print the result.\r\n\r\n<div style=\"background-color: #E0D1EC; border: 1px solid #9660bf; border-radius: 5px; font-size: 1.1em; padding: 15px; margin-bottom: 10px;\">\r\n💡 <strong>TIP:</strong> The result of <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">compareTo()</code> tells you:\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>A negative number = the typed word comes before the dictionary word</li>\r\n  <li>Zero = the words are equal</li>\r\n  <li>A positive number = the typed word comes after the dictionary word</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>\r\n",
